What is the best thing that has ever happened to you for being nice?
This question previously had details. They are now in a comment.
Adam Taha
Writing about life experiences · Author has 5K answers and 94.5M answer views · 7y ·
Originally Answered: What is the best thing that ever happened to you for being nice?

I used to live in city where people’s spirit was down. People were not feeling good, jobs were lost, factories closed down and things was turning for the worse. I saw people losing it.

The way so many were talking didn’t give much hope for younger people either.

There were things that people could access such as funding but they didn’t know where, how, what and when. Only the big organisations were tapping into them while small businesses and people who had passion to do something in the community found themselves lost in the lack of communication.

So I had an idea to lift the city spirits up but it was going to be a huge challenge.

I didn’t even know how to do this, and i didn’t have the tools. Nor did I have the money for it because by time I worked, paid bills and tax took chunk, I didn’t have much.

But I believed and had already had examples in my own life, that anything is possible, if you just do it.

And doing it is what I did.

It was time for a mesage where change needs to happen and it needed a positive voice, showing talents in the city, businesses, organisations and stories from elders who lived here for years, and from young too.

I got to work visiting businesses and people in the community doing interviews, stories, that were positive. Then went to all the funders to find out information how funding for people can be accessed.

And got to work typing it all and then designing the layout of the magazine.

When I came home from work, I was tired but I just hit the shower, had something to eat and got to work. Everyday, 7 days a week, till 3am in morning I worked on this magazine. I didn’t know how much work it would take until I started it.

But I kept going day in, night out.

After some hard work for two month I got the first issue done but now I needed to find the funds. However, the answer was right in front of me. One of the interviews I did talked about a pot of money, lots of it.

So I went to them, showed them the work and they had to spend the thousands of dollars or it goes back. They gave me the money ONLY for that reason.

The final piece is I put a photo of me on back with a final message to the city.

I got the money for the printing and when 30,000 was printed, I hit the streets. Delivering each copy myself, from one business to another, from one organisation to another, from one house to another.

I didn’t have a car back then and so, it was a matter of taken a trolly and doing it by foot and sometimes by bus.

I gave the magazine for free.

Took me a while but as I got them all delivered and kept one copy for myself, which I still have today.

Well, after it was all done, I didn’t think much of it.

Then something strange kept happening.

When I went out to buy something, the shop keepers didn’t want me to pay! They gave me whatever I wanted just like that.

When I wanted to get my head shaved, they didn’t want me to pay. They just did it with a smile. When I went for a drink at the bar, they didn’t want me to pay and just served me a drink and said it was on the house.

When I went to the night clubs, the bouncers shouted me to come in front of que and the club owner didn’t want me to pay.

They just let me walk right in.

I was now holding the key to the city.

Then I got a phone call and..

“We like to fund your second issue.”

I was at first wondering how long it took to do the first one. I asked for more so I can hire people but they will only give me the same. I didn’t want to lower the copies I wanted to print for hiring.

I agreed to do another copy and so the work began again, and through same process, hard work, late night and printed.

But when I went to get the magazine delivered, people saw me and stared helping. Some also came in their cars and went and delivered some. The second issue went out there faster.

Though I couldn’t solve lots of the cities problems, people knew where to get funding. They knew who was who. It sparked off other people to want to do their own magazine, their own creative ideas.

I still, sometimes go back to the city I lived in and there are times when someone remembers me and it happens again..

“Nah mate. You’re not paying. It’s on the house!”

And there, sitting next to glossy magazine is an old, worn out cover of one of the magazine I did. I sometimes wonder how the hell did I do it.

It’s true..

“People will forget what you said. People will forget what you did. But people will never forget how you made them feel.”

I suppose the magazine made them feel something…
